{"id":"id-2"},
{}Amazon S3 Select produces each result for the following reasons:

{"id":"id-1"} â S3Object[0].Rules[0].id produced a match.

{} â S3Object[0].Rules[1].id did not match a record, so Amazon S3 Select emitted MISSING, which was then changed to an empty record during output serialization and returned.

{"id":"id-2"} â S3Object[0].Rules[2].id produced a match.

{} â S3Object[1] did not match on Rules, so Amazon S3 Select emitted MISSING, which was then changed to an empty record during output serialization and returned.
If you don't want Amazon S3 Select to return empty records when it doesn't find a match, you can test for the value MISSING. The following query returns the same results as the previous query, but with the empty values omitted:SELECT id FROM S3Object[*].Rules[*].id WHERE id IS NOT MISSING{"id":"id-1"},
